</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1323,284,510]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
This species will key close to 
<taxonomicName authority="Dash and Viraktamath" authorityName="Dash and Viraktamath" box="[671,1163,324,350]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Deltocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jagannathi" subGenus="Recilia">
<emphasis box="[671,889,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">D. (R.) jagannathi</emphasis>
Dash and Viraktamath
</taxonomicName>
in the key of 
<bibRefCitation author="Dash" box="[264,621,364,390]" pageId="2" pageNumber="5" refString="Dash, P. C. &amp; Viraktamath, C. A. (1998) A review of the Indian and Nepalese grass feeding leafhopper genus Deltocephalus (Homoptera: Cicadellidae) with description of new species. Hexapoda, 10 (1 &amp; 2), 1 - 59." type="journal article" year="1998">
Dash and Viraktamath (
<number box="[549,613,364,390]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1998.0">1998</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. It resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[789,1009,364,389]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Deltocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jagannathi" subGenus="Recilia">
<emphasis box="[789,1009,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">D. (R.) jagannathi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a slender, elongated aedeagal shaft but differs distinctly in not having a bisinuated aedeagal shaft, and in the shape of the apophyses of styles. This species is named 
<taxonomicName box="[1019,1107,444,469]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Deltocephalus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="delongi">
<emphasis box="[1019,1107,444,469]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">delongi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the honour of Dwight Moore Delong, a renowned leafhopper taxonomist.
</paragraph>
